    <item>
      <title>Running Splunk Saved Searches Powered by Tokens From Lookups</title>
      <link>https://dominikbritz.com/posts/2020-11-02-using-lookups-as-token-input/</link>
      <pubDate>Mon, 02 Nov 2020 00:00:00 +0000</pubDate>
      
      <guid>https://dominikbritz.com/posts/2020-11-02-using-lookups-as-token-input/</guid>
      <description>&lt;p&gt;For a new feature in version 6.0 of uberAgent, we needed to run a few saved searches to do some calculations but let users modify input values.&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;Our requirements in detail:&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;ol&gt;
&lt;li&gt;Run saved searches to calculate experience scores for machines, user sessions, and applications&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;li&gt;Provide defaults for thresholds and weights but let users configure them. Users might make modifications once or twice, but not daily. So we needed something easy to understand but nothing too fancy.&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;li&gt;Only administrators should modify settings that should be valid for all users accessing a particular Splunk app. It needed to be configurable, but not for everyone. A poor man&amp;rsquo;s access control, so to say.&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;/ol&gt;
&lt;p&gt;I explain below how we achieved that by using Splunk anywhere examples. That&amp;rsquo;s probably easier to understand, and I don&amp;rsquo;t have to explain every bit of uberAgent here 😉&lt;/p&gt;</description>
      <media:content xmlns:media="http://search.yahoo.com/mrss/" url="https://dominikbritz.com/posts/2020-11-02-using-lookups-as-token-input/featured.jpg" />
    </item>
    
    <item>
      <title>Introducing vlDeploy - Deploy Applications With PowerShell Remotely</title>
      <link>https://dominikbritz.com/posts/2020-03-17-introducing-vldeploy/</link>
      <pubDate>Tue, 17 Mar 2020 00:00:00 +0000</pubDate>
      
      <guid>https://dominikbritz.com/posts/2020-03-17-introducing-vldeploy/</guid>
      <description>&lt;p&gt;Managing applications on Windows in enterprises is complex and cumbersome. Admins are using a variety of tools to install, uninstall or reconfigure applications silently. The most popular tool is propably Microsoft&amp;rsquo;s ConfigMgr.&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;While ConfigMgr (and others) makes sense for mid to large enterprises, the management is too time-consuming for smaller firms. I work in such a smaller firm. We have a lab to test our own applications &lt;a href=&#34;https://uberagent.com&#34; target=&#34;_blank&#34;&gt;uberAgent&lt;/a&gt; on several operating systems. These lab machines don&amp;rsquo;t only run uberAgent, of course, they also run standard applications like text editors, browsers, and more complex things.&lt;/p&gt;</description>
      <media:content xmlns:media="http://search.yahoo.com/mrss/" url="https://dominikbritz.com/posts/2020-03-17-introducing-vldeploy/featured2.png" />
    </item>
    
